snippet.textDisplay:
It’s a long way from killing F1.
BUT.....
The future is NOT fossil fuel based, it simply cannot be. Fossil fuels are finite, humankind is using up the resources at an alarming rate, when you consider that they only came into major use during the industrial revolution (1750-1800) and prior to that we relied on wood burning for most of our heating requirements, although coal /oil was used it wasn’t at a scale that was depleting the resource at a high rate. So fossil fuel has had barely 200 years of use and we are already closing oilfields, reducing its usage and we have to move onto more sustainable power sources. We cannot be reliant on fossil fuels, the countries who have large reserves are becoming unreliable or are already too powerful. Time to develop hydrogen technologies, reduce reliance on fossil fuel, improve battery technology, improve the production of electricity (no point using a coal or oil power station to produce electricity), reduce the damage being done when gathering the required elements for battery tech, move transport and motorsport forward.
F1 has morphed during its existence, it’s improved the technology that goes into road cars, it’s made safety a requirement not a byproduct, it will simply have to push manufacturers towards new tech that will produce fast, interesting and sustainable racing cars. It won’t die, it’ll adapt. It always has, it always will.

snippet.textDisplay: Here's my thoughts on the matter and additions to the speculation zone. 1. Formula E is already in rapid ascendancy over F1. A lot of F1 talent is competing in Formula E and in some cases produce better racing. As much as I love F1, it's becoming a tired platform and the shake up in 2021 needs to turn heads to keep it competing with Formula E. I can easily see Formula E becoming the pinnacle of racing with a merger with F1 when combustion engines cease to exist. One important note is that  Formula E was granted World Championship status back in December by the FIA. Only 2 other series share this title, F1 and WRC. This signals to me a possible switch from the FIA of its preferred race series in the future. 2. WEC and it's Hypercar program. The new hypercar group in WEC starting next year will carry the torch for internal combustion engines for the foreseeable future. Electric Endurance events is not possible with recharging. So if F1 flops, you can get your kicks from WEC. 3. Renault are actively researching electric vehicles along with their partners at Nissan. The road going Zoe and Leaf respectively have had refreshed looks and upgrades and the ranges are getting greater and greater challenging the stranglehold over the market that Tesla has. I just don't think this is down to VW but a whole shift from all manufacturers and I think Tesla is still leading the way. 4. My personal opinion on Electric vehicles is mixed. Formula E is a fantastic racing series to watch and even WRX are getting an electric car. The ranges of electric cars are approaching 300 miles in a single charge and for me that's the magic number in the UK to get people buying the cars. But as someone who respects and loves modded cars, that will die out when the last engine is produced. There will be some brave souls out there keeping the modded cars alive. But you can't mod electric cars. I mean aesthetically yes but engine was it's not possible. The old ways of slapping a turbo on it, engine/drive train conversions will go away. And that's what makes me sad. There's something so animalistic with engines, the smells, the noise and the overall feeling it can't be replicated by the smooth and quiet motors of the electric generation. Sorry for long post.
